&lt;p>SSHAM will use this key in order to connect to the remote hosts.&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Overview</title><link>https://ssham.pacoorozco.info/about/overview/</link><pubDate>Tue, 01 Mar 2022 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://ssham.pacoorozco.info/about/overview/</guid><description>&lt;p>Secure Shell, or Secure Socket Shell — commonly abbreviated as SSH — is a &lt;a
 class="gdoc-markdown__link"
 href="https://www.ssh.com/ssh/protocol/"
>secure network protocol&lt;/a> that allows users to securely authenticate to remote devices. SSH keys are used to access the &lt;a
 class="gdoc-markdown__link"
 href="https://www.ssh.com/ssh/protocol/"
>SSH protocol&lt;/a>. SSH leverages a pair of SSH keys to encrypt communication with a remote system. The key pair is cryptographic in nature and made up of a &lt;em>public&lt;/em> and &lt;em>private key&lt;/em>. The keys work in tandem to provide authentication between the client and the remote system.&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Application defaults</title><link>https://ssham.pacoorozco.info/using-ssham/configuration/app-defaults/</link><pubDate>Tue, 10 May 2022 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://ssham.pacoorozco.info/using-ssham/configuration/app-defaults/</guid><description>&lt;figure>&lt;img src="https://ssham.pacoorozco.info/app-defaults.jpg">
